<BaseLayout title="Kambar & his Ramayanam">
  <p class="es-eyebrow">The poet and the making of the Tamil Ramayanam</p>
  <h1>Kambar &amp; his Ramayanam</h1>
  <p class="hero-lede" style="margin-left:0">
    Kambar (Kavichakravarti, "emperor of poets") composed the Kamba Ramayanam in Tamil in
    the great tradition of Valmiki. Cherished by devotees is the story of how his work came
    to be — sanctioned by an Alvar, honoured by the greatest scholars of the age, and
    blessed by the Lord Himself.
  </p>

  <section class="layer kambar-legend">
    <h2>1. Nammalvar's grace — the calling to write</h2>
    <ImageSlot id="kambar-arangetram-chidambaram" label="Nammalvar's grace & the Chidambaram acceptance" ratio="3/2" />
    <p>
      Before he began, Kambar sought the grace of <strong>Nammalvar</strong>. The Alvar
      appeared to him in a dream at Srirangam, blessed the undertaking, and instructed him
      to compose the <strong>Sathagopar Anthadhi</strong> in his praise. Kambar composed its
      hundred verses in a single night and offered them at Nammalvar's sannidhi. Pleased by
      his devotion, Nammalvar granted his blessing — and so the Ramayanam was begun under an
      Alvar's grace.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="layer kambar-legend">
    <h2>2. The Thillai Mūvāyiravar — the scholars' acceptance</h2>
    <p>
      Kambar wished to present his Ramayanam before the <strong>Thillai Mūvāyiravar</strong>
      — the three thousand hereditary priests and Vedic scholars of Chidambaram, the
      foremost of the age. Reluctant to hear it, they were gathered (so the tradition tells)
      at the cremation ground around the body of a boy who had died of snakebite. One
      challenged him: <em>"If the power of your Ramayanam is real, let this child live
      again."</em> Kambar recited the verse describing Garuda's arrival — at which the
      serpents fled from Rama and Lakshmana — and by the power of that poetry the poison
      left the child, and he rose alive. Astonished, the Dikshitars accepted and honoured
      Kambar's work.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="layer kambar-legend">
    <h2>3. Narasimha's blessing at Srirangam</h2>
    <ImageSlot id="kambar-narasimha-blessing" label="Narasimha blesses Kambar's Ramayanam" ratio="3/2" />
    <p>
      At last Kambar offered his completed Ramayanam before the Lord at Srirangam. The Lord,
      as the radiant <strong>Narasimha</strong>, gave His blessing upon the work — the divine
      seal that crowned the poet's labour. So the Kamba Ramayanam went forth, sanctioned by
      Alvar, scholar, and the Lord alike.
    </p>
  </section>

  <p class="es-note"><small>These are the traditional accounts cherished about Kambar; details vary in the telling. Images are original devotional art (see the About page on sources &amp; method).</small></p>
